					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Alg=
ebraic operation on coordinate vectors</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"Scalar prod=
uct" redirects here. For the more general concept of an inner product, see =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_product_space" title=3D"Inne=
r product space">Inner product space</a>. For the product of a vector and a=
 scalar, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_multiplication=
" title=3D"Scalar multiplication">Scalar multiplication</a>.</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>dot product</b> is an <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_operation" title=3D"Algebraic operation">algeb=
raic operation</a> that takes two equal-length sequences of numbers (usuall=
y <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinate_vector" title=3D"Coor=
dinate vector">coordinate vectors</a>), and returns a single number. In <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidea=
n geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, the <b>scalar product</b><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_p=
roduct#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=3D"Euclidean vector">vectors</a> is the d=
ot product of their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coor=
dinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cartesian coordinates">Cartesian co=
ordinates</a>, and is independent from the choice of a particular Cartesian=
 coordinate system. The terms "dot product" and "scalar product" are often =
used interchangeably when a Cartesian coordinate system has been fixed once=
 for all. The scalar product being a particular <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Inner_product" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inner product">=
inner product</a>, the term "inner product" is also often used.=20
</p><p>Algebraically, the dot product is the sum of the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_(mathematics)" title=3D"Product (mathematics)=
">products</a> of the corresponding entries of the two sequences of numbers=
. Geometrically, the scalar product of two vectors is the product of their =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector#Length" title=3D"=
Euclidean vector">lengths</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Cosine" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cosine">cosine</a> of the angle =
between them. These definitions are equivalent when using Cartesian coordin=
ates. In modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D=
"Geometry">geometry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean=
_space" title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean spaces</a> are often defined by=
 using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vect=
or space">vector spaces</a>. In this case, the scalar product is used for d=
efining lengths (the length of a vector is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">square root</a> of the scal=
ar product of the vector by itself) and angles (the cosine of the angle bet=
ween two vectors is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotient" =
title=3D"Quotient">quotient</a> of their scalar product by the product of t=
heir lengths).
</p><p>The name "dot product" is derived from the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Dot_operator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dot operator">=
dot operator</a> "&nbsp;<b>=E2=8B=85</b>&nbsp;" that is often used to desig=
nate this operation;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_product#cite_note-:1-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
the alternative name "scalar product" emphasizes that the result is a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_(mathematics)" title=3D"Scalar (=
mathematics)">scalar</a>, rather than a vector (as with the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_product" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ve=
ctor product">vector product</a> in three-dimensional space).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDot_product&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The dot product may be defined algebraically or geometrically. The geome=
tric definition is based on the notions of angle and distance (<a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnitude_(mathematics)" title=3D"Magnitude (m=
athematics)">magnitude</a>) of vectors. The equivalence of these two defini=
tions relies on having a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian=
_coordinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cartesian coordin=
ate system</a> for Euclidean space.
</p><p>In modern presentations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, th=
e points of space are defined in terms of their <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cartesi=
an coordinates">Cartesian coordinates</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space" title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean space</a>=
 itself is commonly identified with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Real_coordinate_space" title=3D"Real coordinate space">real coordinat=
e space</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
style \mathbf {R} ^{n}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">R</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {R} ^=
{n}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5ed657d7f0d7aa156e7b9b171f22b4a3aa6482c3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:3.222ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbf {R} ^{n}}"></span>. In such a presentation, the notions of length and =
angle are defined by means of the dot product. The length of a vector is de=
fined as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" title=3D=
"Square root">square root</a> of the dot product of the vector by itself, a=
nd the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosine" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Cosine">cosine</a> of the (non oriented) angle between two vect=
ors of length one is defined as their dot product. So the equivalence of th=
e two definitions of the dot product is a part of the equivalence of the cl=
assical and the modern formulations of Euclidean geometry.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Coordinate_definition">Coor=
dinate definition</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DDot_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Coordinate definition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The dot product of two vectors <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-=
element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y"=
 style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML=
